│ ### Root Cause Analysis ###                                                         │
│                                                                                     │
│ -------------------- BEGIN --------------------                                     │
│ 1. Understanding the Issue:                                                         │
│ The pass crashes in unfold() with the assertion SI->use_empty() && "Select must be  │
│ dead now". This indicates that after performing the select unfolding                │
│ transformation, the original SelectInst still has at least one remaining use,       │
│ violating the assumption that it becomes dead.                                      │
│                                                                                     │
│ 2. Analyzing opt's Log:                                                             │
│ The debug log shows the pass identifies the switch in block select.unfold as a      │
│ candidate, and recognizes both %spec.select7 and %spec.select as relevant selects.  │
│ The crash occurs during the first transformation point in unfold(). From the        │
│ debugger, SI is %spec.select, and SIUse (the PHI in select.unfold) still has an     │
│ incoming of %spec.select from bb1, plus new incoming edges created by prior unfold  │
│ steps, confirming the select isn't dead.                                            │
│                                                                                     │
│ 3. Root Cause Analysis:                                                             │
│ The unfolding logic for the unconditional predecessor case                          │
│ (StartBlockTerm->isUnconditional()) replaces the PHI's incoming value from          │
│ StartBlock with SIOp1 (the 'true' value of the outer select), and adds a new block  │
│ (NewBlock) with a PHI (NewPhi) that carries SIOp2. Specifically, lines 231-237 set  │
│ the PHI's StartBlock incoming to SIOp1. If SIOp1 is itself a SelectInst (an inner   │
│ select scheduled for unfold), this replacement introduces a new direct use of the   │
│ inner select by the PHI. Subsequently, the code at lines 226-229 pushes the inner   │
│ select (SIOp1) onto NewSIsToUnfold with SIUse being the PHI. When unfold() later    │
│ attempts to unfold this inner select, it expects the select to become dead after    │
│ its replacement, but the PHI still directly references it, causing SI->use_empty()  │
│ to fail. The reproducer demonstrates this: %spec.select7's unfolding causes %_2 to  │
│ take %spec.select as an incoming from bb1, leaving %spec.select with a non-empty    │
│ use list.                                                                           │
│                                                                                     │
│ In short, the unconditional path creates a new use of the inner select in the PHI,  │
│ but also schedules that inner select for unfolding against that same PHI, violating │
│ the one-use/deadness assumptions.                                                   │
│                                                                                     │
│ 4. Proposed Edit Point(s):                                                          │
│ Edit llvm/lib/Transforms/Scalar/DFAJumpThreading.cpp lines 226-229 to avoid         │
│ scheduling the inner select (SIOp1) for unfolding when it becomes directly          │
│ referenced by the PHI. Only schedule unfolding for the false operand (SIOp2), which │
│ is routed through NewBlock and NewPhi, preserving the one-use invariant.            │
│                                                                                     │
│ Concrete change:                                                                    │
│ - Remove or guard the push of SelectInstToUnfold(OpSi, SIUse) for SIOp1 in the      │
│ unconditional predecessor path.                                                     │
│ - Keep pushing for SIOp2 with NewPhi.                                               │
│                                                                                     │
│ This prevents attempting to unfold SIOp1 in a context where we've just created an   │
│ additional use for it, avoiding the assertion.                                      │
│                                                                                     │
│ 5. Conclusion:                                                                      │
│ By not scheduling the inner select SIOp1 for unfolding in the unconditional         │
│ predecessor case, we avoid creating a conflict between newly introduced uses and    │
│ the deadness requirement. The pass will still unfold the outer select and the       │
│ false-side select (via NewBlock/NewPhi), while maintaining correctness and          │
│ preventing the crash. This is a conservative fix that addresses the immediate       │
│ assertion failure and aligns with the invariants assumed by unfold().               │
│ --------------------  END  --------------------                                     │
